                    <title>GDCR15 Cross-Event Google Hangouts</title>
                    <link rel="alternate" href="http://coderetreat.org/xn/detail/6456126:Topic:47400"/>
                                        <id>tag:coderetreat.org,2015-10-17:6456126:Topic:47400</id>
                                        <updated>2015-10-17T20:39:02.544Z</updated>
                    
                                            <author>
                            <name>Bob Allen @CuriousAgilist</name>
                            <uri>http://coderetreat.org/profile/BobAllenCuriousAgilist</uri>
                        </author>
                    
                    <summary type="html">
                        &lt;p&gt;Hi All,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Doing a Google hangout with another GDCR event in a faraway time zone helps to bring home the GLOBAL nature of the event to attendees. I&#039;ve used a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.timeanddate.com/worldclock/meeting.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;cross-timezone meeting planner&lt;/a&gt; to determine times that work and have tentatively sent out invites to others for two hangouts; one just before our local lunchtime and another at our end-of-day retrospective. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you like the idea, it&#039;s not rocket…&lt;/p&gt;                    </summary>

                                            <content type="html">
                            &lt;p&gt;Hi All,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Doing a Google hangout with another GDCR event in a faraway time zone helps to bring home the GLOBAL nature of the event to attendees. I&#039;ve used a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.timeanddate.com/worldclock/meeting.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;cross-timezone meeting planner&lt;/a&gt; to determine times that work and have tentatively sent out invites to others for two hangouts; one just before our local lunchtime and another at our end-of-day retrospective. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you like the idea, it&#039;s not rocket science. You need to remain flexible, make sure you agree on the way to communicate &lt;em&gt;beforehand,&lt;/em&gt; and then &lt;em&gt;make sure&lt;/em&gt; to pay attention to the time to make it happen. It may even help to ask someone other that the event facilitator to do that. It&#039;s easy for a facilitator to have so many things going on that they miss the planned window. Bummer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;-- Bob Allen&lt;/p&gt;                        </content>
                    
